ODE XXI.

TO MY CASK.

This poem appears composed in honour of some occasion in which Horace entertained the famous L. Valerius Mes· sala Corvinus. No man in that great age was more re- markable for the variety of his accomplishments than this Corvinus. Sprung from one of the greatest consular fami- lies, he espoused the senatorian party in the civil wars, and attached himself especially to Cassius.
